Asking this magical New Year‚Äôs moose for the best rooftops in #Chicago to celebrate New Year‚Äôs Eveüéá. Here‚Äôs what he told me:

üéä @thegwenchicago ‚Äî if you‚Äôre looking for cozy, chill NYE vibes rather than a huge party, dinner or drinks on The Gwen‚Äôs rooftop (pictured here) may be just the ticket. Their food is phenomenal, and I love the fire pit tables for staying toasty while dining outside. Fire pit tables require a $75 deposit when booking, but regular tables are free!

üéä @offshorerooftop ‚Äî if on the other hand you‚Äôre looking to party, you can‚Äôt do much better than the largest rooftop in the country. Tickets are a pricy $175pp, but (because of Offshore‚Äôs Navy Pier location) they include the absolute best views of this year‚Äôs mega-fireworks display over the lake!

üéä @jparkerchicago ‚Äî another rooftop for great views of the fireworks is J Parker in Lincoln Park. Tickets are $90-125 and include a four-hour open bar, passed appetizers, access to a dessert bar, and a champagne toast at midnight!

üéä @travellechicago ‚Äî Travelle at the @langhamchicago is perfect for foodies with its seven-course prix fixe New Years Eve dinner designed by Executive Chef Damion Henry. We kicked the meal off with crab #rangoons and continued to the mains: Mongolian beef and dry chili chicken. Shockingly, the #beef was my favorite of the three. I say this because I‚Äôm not a bell pepper person. They had some smaller peppers that were lovely, and the crispy noodles under it all soaked up the sauce in the most wonderful way possible. I love that the entrees are served family style but know that‚Äôs not everyone‚Äôs jam (I did a very scientific poll where 35% of you were against family-style meals).

I was in a bit of a rush‚Ä¶ so you‚Äôll just have to deal with the limited photos I was able to snap and trust that you might have to just go there yourself to confirm that their bottles aren‚Äôt blurry.

Chef‚Äôs Special is a Chinese-American restaurant from the same folks who run Giant. They don‚Äôt claim to have secret authentic recipes, and the decor is anything but appropriated. They liked making Chinese food and wanted to share their creations with the public, and they‚Äôre doing so in a way that doesn‚Äôt make me cringe. This isn‚Äôt your typical cheap Chinese fare‚Äîlook elsewhere for the pile of $5 general‚Äôs chicken.

Raviolo all‚Äôuovo, with the obligatory egg yolk shot. I made my own ricotta, but store-bought is just fine as well. Enjoy a nearly-foolproof execution of this‚Äîit‚Äôs a great first course dish!

Timeout Market is a mainstay of West Loop and Chicago as a whole. In the time since it‚Äôs opened, there‚Äôs been a bit of a rotating lineup of eateries. Often representing the best of Chicago‚Äôs neighborhoods, it‚Äôs taken more recent steps to diversify the booths with BIPOC owned restaurants. There‚Äôs a range across the categories of food, from burgers, pizza, Asian food, Italian food, and ice cream; particularly with how it has evolved through the pandemic. The sheer openness of its interior is certainly a factor in both its diverse menus and the people it has brought in. So it‚Äôs easier for me to see it as what it culminates in. A hub for all things food and drink, that caters to brief work lunches and voguish weekend evenings. Five minute lunch breaks, or a whole birthday dinner (as was the case in 2019). Very much itemizing why people come to Chicago for food, all organized into one center-point.
